Churn-Modelling¶

Business Problem¶

The organisation is a large financial institution that services a large number of customers. Recenly , the organisation has noticed an increase in customers who are leaving the organisation and would like to understand why this is happening as well as identify customers who are likely to churn in order to engage and retain those customers. As there is substantial costs involved with reaching customers, the organisation is interested in curating a list of customers to share with its marketing team to begin the engagement process.

Problem Statement¶

There is a significant increase in customers churning over the last 12 months. The organisation is therefore looking to reduce customer churn to < 10% within the next 12 months with the expected benefit of increasing revenue by $55m in the next 12 months

Data Science Activities¶

  1. Conduct exploratory Analysis to understand drivers of Churn
  2. Build an initial model to Identify customers likely to churn

Results:¶

  1. Feature importance refers to the importance of a feature in driving the outcome of churn for each of our respective models as shown above Across all models, Age appears to be the most important driver that impacts churn for our customers followed by their activity and number of products they possess
  1. Both Random Forest Models and Gradient Boosting Models show very good overall performance with a AUC ROC (Area under Curve) score of .95 and .93. High score means both models are very good at identifying customers who will churn. Further, the models also have high recall and precision which is important because:
    • High Recall means lower likelihood of false negatives (we fail to identify churning customers) which is a bad outcome for retention
    • High Precision meaning lower likelihood of false positive (non-churning customers predicted as churning) which is costly to engage

#function to identify multicollinear columns
def collinearity_rem(correlation_matrix, threshold):
    # Create a Mask
    
    collinear_pairs = []
    #traverse diagonal
    for i in range(1,correlation_matrix.shape[0]):
        for j in range(i):
            if abs(correlation_matrix.iloc[i,j]) > threshold:
                collinear_pairs.append((correlation_matrix.columns[i], correlation_matrix.columns[j]))
    
    print("Collinear pairs above threshold:")
    for pair in collinear_pairs: 
        print(f"Variables {pair[0]} and {pair[1]} are highly correlated.")

    # Create a list of variables to remove (only 1 variable from each pair)
    variables_to_remove = set()
    for pair in collinear_pairs:
        variables_to_remove.add(pair[0])

    # Convert set to a list
    variables_to_remove = list(variables_to_remove)
        #converts matrix to a flatmap
    return variables_to_remove

# 2) Split Data Set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=23)


# 3) Initiate your classifier objects
classifiers = [DecisionTreeClassifier(),RandomForestClassifier(),GradientBoostingClassifier()]
classifier_names = ['Decision Tree','Random Forest','Gradient Boost']

# 4) Store your prediction results and begin training your models
results_train = []
results_test = []
results = []

# 5) Print your evaluation metrics + Display feature important 
for clf, name in zip(classifiers,classifier_names):
    pass
    #Train the model
    clf.fit(X_train,y_train)

    #Predict the responses using the trained model and store the predicted responses 
    y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
    y_pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)
    
    #Create a confusion matrix to evaluate
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred)

    #Visualise the confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    #sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, cmap='Blues', fmt = 'g')
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm, display_labels= clf.classes_).plot()
    plt.show()

    #Print evaluation metrics
    print(f"Model: {name}")
    print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred))
    print("Recall:", recall_score(y_test,y_pred))
    print("Precision:", precision_score(y_test,y_pred))
    print("F1 Score:", f1_score(y_test,y_pred))
    print("roc_auc_score", roc_auc_score(y_test,y_pred))

    #Display feature importance
    importances = clf.feature_importances_
    indices = np.argsort(importances)

    plt.clf()
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
    plt.title(f'Feature Importances: {name}')
    plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color='b', align='center')
    plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [X.columns[i] for i in indices])
    plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')
    plt.show()
    plt.clf()

    # Y Scores for AUC Model
    y_scores_train = clf.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1]
    y_scores_test = clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

    # Calculate AUC
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_scores_test)
    print(f'AUC: {auc}')

    # Calculate and visualize ROC curve
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_scores_test, pos_label=0)
    plt.plot(tpr, fpr, label= f'ROC Curve = {auc:0.2f}')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', label='Random Guessing (ROC = 0.5)', color='gray')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title(f'ROC Curve for {name}')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
    #Evaluate and append results
    results_train.append({
        'Classifier': name,
        'Accuracy': accuracy_score(y_train,y_pred_train),
        'Precision': precision_score(y_train, y_pred_train),
        'Recall': recall_score(y_train, y_pred_train),
        'F1': f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train),
        'AUC': roc_auc_score(y_train,y_scores_train)
    })
    results_test.append({
        'Classifier': name,
        'Accuracy': accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred),
        'Precision': precision_score(y_test, y_pred),
        'Recall': recall_score(y_test, y_pred),
        'F1': f1_score(y_test, y_pred),
        'AUC': roc_auc_score(y_test,y_scores_test)
    })

# 5) Initiate a grid search to improve training...

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
import time

# Define the parameter grid

param_grid_dt = {
    'max_depth': np.arange(3, 15),
    'min_samples_split': np.arange(2, 15),
    'min_samples_leaf': np.arange(1, 15),
}

param_grid_gbm = {
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 1],
       'max_depth': [None, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

param_grid_rf = {
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200],
    'max_depth': [None, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}
best_params_all = dict()


# Create a Random Forest Classifier with the parameter grid
classifier_names = ['Decision Tree','Random Forest','Gradient Boost']

for clf, param_grid, name in zip(classifiers,[param_grid_dt,param_grid_rf,param_grid_gbm],classifier_names):
#for clf, param_grid in zip(classifiers,[param_grid_dt]):
    start_time = time.time()

    # Instantiate the grid search model
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=clf, param_grid=param_grid, cv=2)

    # Fit the grid search to the data
    grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

    end_time = time.time()
    elapsed_time = end_time - start_time

    # Get the best parameters
    best_params_all[name] = grid_search.best_params_

    print(f'Best parameters for {name}: {best_params_all[name]}/n')

    # Train the model with best parameters
    best_grid = grid_search.best_estimator_
    best_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predict the response for the test dataset
    y_pred = best_grid.predict(X_test)

    # Create a confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    cmd = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm)
    cmd.plot()
    plt.show()

    # Print evaluation metrics
    print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("Precision:", precision_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("Recall:", recall_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("F1 score:", f1_score(y_test, y_pred))

    print(f"Hyperparameter tuning took: {elapsed_time:.2f} seconds")
